from the gridfs spec:
{quote}
writeConcern: defaults to the write concern on the parent database (or client object if the parent database has no write concern).
readPreference: defaults to the read preference on the parent database (or client object if the parent database has no read preference).
{quote}

Since there is no db object in the c driver's gridfs, should it be the client's then?  I think the gridfs spec was written before read_concern was a thing, but I imagine the same would apply for that?

I see; I'll have to be more selective in how we translate queries.

Old plan:
{code}
$query -> filter
$orderby -> sort
$showDiskLoc -> showRecordId
$anything-else -> anything-else
{code}

New plan:
{code}
$query -> filter
$orderby -> sort
$hint -> hint
$comment -> comment
$maxScan -> maxScan
$maxTimeMS -> maxTimeMS
$max -> max
$min -> min
$returnKey -> returnKey
$showDiskLoc -> showRecordId
$snapshot -> snapshot
$anything-else -> ensure "filter" and push $anything-else into "filter" document
{code}

So this:
{code}
{$or: [a, b]}
{code}
is no longer translated into:
{code}
{find: "collection", or: [a, b], filter: {}}
{code}
Instead, it'll become:
{code}
{find: "collection", filter: {$or: [a, b]}}
{code}

